class Solution {
public:
    bool makeStringsEqual(string s, string target) {
        int countS = 0, countT = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i < s.size(); i++) {
            countS += s[i] - '0';
            countT += target[i] - '0';
        }
        return (countS == 0 && countT == 0) || (countS > 0 && countT > 0);
    }
};
```
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(n)
space complexity: O(1)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: The approach counts the number of 1's in both strings. If both counts are 0 or both are greater than 0, it's possible to make s equal to target; otherwise, it's not.

